By convention these features are identified on lunar maps by placing the letter on the side of the crater midpoint that is closest to Piccolomini.

translation is a translation in which the source text is translated literally, with only minor changes to word choice or grammar.

A calque may be a literal translation, or it may be an adaptation of the source text to make it more suitable for the target language. The translation may be faithful or free, depending on the degree to which the original text is used.

The use of calque can be traced back to the days of Classical Latin, when translations were often made from Greek and other ancient languages into Latin. In later centuries, calques were used in law, medicine, and other academic fields, as well as in popular culture.

beyond the solar system, located around the star Kepler-10. It was announced in May 2016 by the Kepler team and confirmed in October 2016 by follow-up observations.

Kepler-10 is a sun-like star located about 1,000 light years from Earth in the constellation Cygnus. It is one of the few stars that has been monitored by Kepler, which found numerous planets transiting its surface. In particular, Kepler-10b was found to have two transits, indicating that it may be a terrestrial planet. Further observations were needed to confirm this.

Buddhism practiced by the Newar people of Nepal. It is a distinct form of Buddhism that has developed in Nepal over the centuries, and has some unique features.

Newar Buddhism is based on the Tantric practice of chakrasamvara, which is said to be able to achieve Enlightenment. The practice involves using mantras and visualisations to connect with the various chakras in the body. Newar Buddhism is also known for its reverence for goddesses, including Parvati, Lakshmi, and Tara.

the Indianapolis Motor Speedway on May 29, 1985. The race was won by A. J. Foyt, driving a Chevrolet driven by manager/owner Ray Evernham. Al Unser, Jr. finished second in a Penske Racing Ford, and Cale Yarborough finished third in a Lola-Ford.

The race was contested over 267 laps of the Indianapolis Motor Speedway's 2.5-mile oval. It was the first time that the Indy 500 had been televised live in its entirety; the race was also the first time that the race was broadcast in high definition. The race's official attendance was 281,070, making it the largest crowd to ever witness an Indy 500 event.

In 1983, after 34 years of competition, reigning champion Mario Andretti retired from racing at the age of 48. His last competitive event would be the 1983 Indianapolis 500; Andretti finished sixth in his last Indy 500 race.

Two other drivers who would go on to win numerous races during their careers made their Indy 500 debuts at this race: Kenny Brack (driving for Team Penske) and Rick Mears (driving for McLaren).

The city's namesake was a member of the Texas House of Representatives and later the Texas Governor who helped organize and promote the town. By 1886, Richardson had a population of 700 and was the county seat of Dallas County. The city became known as the "Queen City of the South" because of its numerous cotton plantations. The cotton industry declined in the 1930s, however, and by the 1970s most of the plantations had been sold or abandoned.

struck the Philippines on September 13, 2006. The system became a tropical storm on September 13 and strengthened into a typhoon the next day. Maria made landfall on the central Philippines on September 15 and weakened rapidly over the next two days. The system dissipated over the South China Sea on September 18. 

Maria was the eighteenth typhoon of the 2006 Pacific typhoon season and caused at least fifteen fatalities, ten of which were in the Philippines. Damage totaled $100 million (2006 USD).

literary heritage, which is evident in the many written works that have been produced over the centuries. Laos has a long and profound literary tradition, dating back to the ancient times. Today, Laos boasts some of the best writers in Southeast Asia, and the country is home to both traditional and contemporary literature.

The literary traditions of Laos date back to antiquity. The earliest written records of Lao culture date back to the 3rd century BC, when the historian and philosopher Fa-Hien travelled to Lao PDR. Fa-Hien was one of the most famous translators and travellers of his time, and he left behind a detailed account of Lao culture and history. His work, The Travels of Fa-Hien, is one of the most important sources of information about Lao culture and history.

Lao literature flourished during the Sui and Tang dynasties (AD 590-907 and 907-1279). The literati of this period were highly educated, and they produced a number of classical works, including poetry, prose fiction, and historical writings. These works are characterized by their elegant prose style and richly descriptive language.

The iris is a genus of around 100â€“150 species of flowering plants in the family Iridaceae. The genus is widespread across much of Europe, Asia, and North America, with a few species in Africa and South America. Many of the species are cultivated as garden plants. The name Iris comes from the Greek word for rainbow, probably because the flowers of many irises are multicolored.

Some irises are cultivated for their flowers, while others are used as garden plants or for landscaping. Some are selectively bred for various traits, such as large flowers or hardiness in cold climates. Iris sambucina is usually grown as an ornamental plant in temperate regions.

Natalia Gvishiani was born on October 2, 1962 in Moscow, USSR. She began her studies at the Moscow State Linguistic University in 1981, majoring in Russian philology. In 1988 she earned her doctorate in Russian linguistics.

In 1991 Gvishiani emigrated to the United States and began working at the University of California, Berkeley as a linguistics lecturer. In 1995 she joined the faculty of the University of Pennsylvania, where she is currently a professor of Russian and East European studies.

Gvishiani's research focuses on Russian language and literature, with a particular focus on 19th century Russian literature. She has written extensively on Leo Tolstoy, Anton Chekhov, and Nikolai Gogol, among others. She has also published essays on Russian language education, contemporary Russian culture, and Slavic linguistics.

Chavez's work has been influential in the field of Chicano studies and he has been described as "the father of Chicano studies". The 2001 Peach Bowl was a college football bowl game played on December 26, 2001 at Atlantaâ€“Fulton County Stadium in Atlanta, Georgia. It was the 37th edition of the Peach Bowl, and featured the North Carolina Tar Heels of the Atlantic Coast Conference (ACC) against the Texas Tech Red Raiders of the Big 12 Conference.

The Tar Heels entered the game as 10-point underdogs, but upset Texas Tech 31-24 to earn their fourth bowl win in six years. North Carolina quarterback T. J. Yates threw for a career-high 422 yards and four touchdowns, while running back Lorenzo White rushed for 131 yards and two scores.
